In order to solve for the net present value, we will use this formula:

$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Net present value}&=\text{Present value cash flow}−\text{Initial investment}\\
&−\text{Net working capital}
\end{aligned}$$

The present value cash flow can be solved using this formula:

$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Present value cash flow}&=\dfrac{\text{OCF Year 1}-\text{Net working capital Year 1}}{(1+0.09)^1}+\dfrac{\text{OCF Year 2}-\text{Net working capital Year 2}}{(1+0.09)^2}\\
&+\dfrac{\text{OCF Year 3}-\text{Net working capital Year 3}}{(1+0.09)^3}+\dfrac{\text{OCF Year 4}-\text{Net working capital Year 4}}{(1+0.09)^4}\\
&+\dfrac{\text{OCF Year 5}+\text{Net working capital Year 5}+\text{After-tax salvage value}}{(1+0.09)^5}
\end{aligned}$$
